#This has to be the easiest one to start with aside CO-STAR & JSON based prompts...

#So what do I mean to do in this file?
#It's quite simple really. HR already spends little to no time checking candidate CVs.
#There is a risk though. Because the opportunity cost for this revolves around quality vs efficiency.
#On one hand HR can keep up the efficiency and let AI analyse and summarise candidate CVs for them
#or they can opt for quality in which case they are actually actively looking into CVs for potential candidate yield.
#There is a way to balance these 2 however, with little to no risk.
#This is where Prompt Engineering becomes the main topic of this whole process.
#It's way easier to have a HR team that can work with LLMs because this way we can eliminate the opportunity cost entirely.
#This should serve as an example of how an HR team can implement this within their department.

#The comparison bases

{
  "student_eligibility_criterias": {
  "isEmployed": false,
  "LookingForInternship": true,
  "isStudent": true,
  "city": "Same as HQ or close"
  }
}

#Above you can see a simple student eligibility criteria for an internship
#As you can see there are certain namespaces which define the criteria for the student(s)
#isEmployed for example, will tell the AI that you are mainly looking for students which don't already have job
#This filters out a criteria set by HR
#Lets now see below how the prompt would look like for an LLM to work out the filtering using CO-STAR and JSON

PROMPT:
{
  "context": "Student CV filtering based on JSON document criteria",
  "objective": "Determine which of the attatched CVs is eligible for an internship",
  "style": "Human Resources",
  "input_data": {
    "primary": "Student_criteria.json",
    "secondary": [{"CV1.pdf", "CV2.pdf, ... , "CVn.pdf"]
  },
  "logic_rules": {
    "match_on": "student_eligibility_criterias",
    "if_mismatch": "Flag in red text",
    "writeVerdict": "Student eligibility"
  },
  "output_format": "text"
}

